<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1934,2031]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,501]" lastPageId="4" pageId="3">
Color in Preservative. Dorsal surface of head dark olive, paler on the scale margins, becoming paler and more yellow anteriorly and laterally; nasals, loreals, preoculars, and supralabials pale yellow-olive with gray smudges on the dorsal margins of supralabials 
<number box="[537,580,2006,2031]" pageId="3" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5</number>
where they meet the loreals, preocular, and tiny suboculars; dark gray spots on the ventral margins of supralabials 
<number box="[581,627,152,176]" pageId="4" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
; preoculars with gray spots next to eye; temporal region olive with gray spots in the centers of the temporal scales and the sixth supralabial. Infralabials and ventral surface of head light yellow-olive. Dorsum olive; 
<number box="[473,501,224,248]" pageId="4" value="19.0">19</number>
faint lines composed of gray spots in the scale centers, some of which extend to the end of the tail; the lines become more faint towards the ventral surface. Venter pale yellow-olive.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,295,320]" pageId="4">Habitat.</emphasis>
The single specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[590,697,296,320]" class="Reptilia" family="Anguidae" genus="Ophiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="luciae">
<emphasis box="[590,697,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4">
<collectingCountry box="[590,613,296,319]" name="Iceland" pageId="4">O</collectingCountry>
. luciae
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was taken in Wet Chaco (
<bibRefCitation author="Dinerstein" box="[1008,1267,295,320]" pageId="4" refString="Dinerstein, E., Olson, D., Graham, D., Webster, A., Primm, S., Bookbinder, M. &amp; Ledec, G. (1995) Evaluacion del estado de conservacion de las ecorregiones terrestres de America Latina y el Caribe. World Wildlife Fund, Banco Mundial, Washington, D. C., xxviii, 135 pp." type="book" year="1995">
Dinerstein 
<emphasis box="[1138,1190,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1208,1267,295,320]" pageId="4" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), in a savanna composed of palms (
<taxonomicName box="[390,575,332,356]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Copernicia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="4" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[390,575,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="4">Copernicia alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), native bunch grasses, and bare ground, with small interspersed islands of semideciduous forest. The savanna floods periodically from the 
<collectingCountry box="[870,974,368,392]" name="Paraguay" pageId="4">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
River (
<figureCitation box="[1059,1127,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[162,1421,1134,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[162,1422,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Elevation map of the type locality (black dot) and surroundings. Areas in dark green (50 – 80 masl) are periodically flooded." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238539/files/figure.png" pageId="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1111,1127,367,392]" pageId="4" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,404,428]" pageId="4">Etymology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[343,529,404,428]" class="Reptilia" family="Anguidae" genus="Ophiodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="luciae">
<emphasis box="[343,529,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="4">Ophiodes luciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named in honor of our colleague and good friend Aida Luz (Lucy) Aquino, who has worked for more than thirty years on the biology, distribution, and conservation of the Paraguayan herpetofauna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
